âŒ  <thinking>  or  [reasoning]  or any XML tags
âŒ Code blocks: \`\`\`json { "characters": [...] } \`\`\`
âŒ "name": "John", "He is tall and strong", "age": 25
   (orphaned description without property name)
âŒ "physical" "brown hair and blue eyes"
   (missing colon)
âŒ "aliases": ["John", "Scout",]
   (trailing comma)
âŒ Here's the analysis: { "characters": [...] }
   (text before JSON)

âœ… CORRECT FORMAT ONLY:
{
  "characters": [
    {
      "name": "Full Name",
      "physical": "description here",
      "aliases": ["nick1", "nick2"]
    }
  ]
}

âš ï¸ VALIDATION CHECK: Before responding, verify:
1. Starts with { immediately (no text before)
2. Every string has opening AND closing quotes
3. Every property has a colon after the name
4. No orphaned text without property names
5. Ends with } immediately (no text after)

ONLY include characters mentioned in these specific messages or with new information
DO NOT repeat unchanged characters from the Current Lorebook Entries

DO NOT include:
- Any text before the JSON
- Any text after the JSON
- Code block markers like \`\`\`json
- Explanations, commentary, or thinking tags
- XML tags like  <thinking>  or  [reasoning]  (these break JSON parsing)

REQUIRED JSON structure (copy this exact format):
{
  "characters": [
    {
      "name": "Full character name (SINGLE NAME ONLY - never include aliases here)",
      "aliases": ["Alternative names for THIS SAME person - nicknames, shortened names, titles"],
      "physicalAge": "Age if mentioned",
      "mentalAge": "Mental age if different",
      "physical": "Physical description",
      "personality": "Personality traits",
      "sexuality": "Sexual orientation if mentioned",
      "raceEthnicity": "Race/ethnicity if mentioned",
      "roleSkills": "Job/role/skills",
      "relationships": ["currentchar, otherchar, relationship"],
      "confidence": 75
    }
  ]
}

CRITICAL FIELD SPECIFICATIONS:

NAME FIELD RULES:
- Use the MOST COMPLETE proper name mentioned (e.g., "John Blackwood")
- NEVER include commas, slashes, or multiple names in the name field
- NEVER combine name + alias (âŒ "John Blackwood, John" âŒ "John/Scout")
- If only a first name is known, use just that ("John")

ALIASES FIELD RULES:
- Include ALL other ways this character is referred to
- Nicknames, shortened names, titles, alternative spellings
- Examples: ["John", "Scout", "JB", "Mr. Blackwood"]

RELATIONSHIPS FIELD - NATURAL LANGUAGE FORMAT:
ğŸš¨ CRITICAL: ONLY use this format: "Character A is to Character B: relationship1, relationship2"

â›” FORBIDDEN FORMATS:
- "Character, Other, relationship" (OLD TRIPLET FORMAT - DO NOT USE)
- "Character A, Character B, relationship" (OLD TRIPLET FORMAT - DO NOT USE)

âœ… MANDATORY FORMAT: "Character A is to Character B: relationship1, relationship2"

âš ï¸ CRITICAL NAMING REQUIREMENTS:
- ALWAYS use the character's CANONICAL/PREFERRED name in relationships
- If "John Blackwood" is the main name, use "John Blackwood" NOT "John"
- Maintain name consistency across ALL relationship entries
- Multiple relationships for same pair: separate with commas

âœ… CORRECT examples:
- "Dora is to John Blackwood: lover, submissive"
- "Maya is to Sarah Chen: sister, gymnastics partner"
- "John Blackwood is to Julia Martinez: son"
- "Sarah Chen is to John Blackwood: rival, former colleague"

âŒ FORBIDDEN patterns:
- "Dora, John, lover" (OLD FORMAT - NEVER USE)
- "Dora, John Blackwood, lover" (OLD FORMAT - NEVER USE)
- "John, Jasmine, friend" (OLD FORMAT - NEVER USE)
- "Dora is to John: lover" + "Dora is to John Blackwood: lover" (inconsistent naming)
- Narrative text: "Living in luxury penthouse since age 17"
- Actions/events: "Takes charge of organizing rescue mission"

ğŸ”„ RELATIONSHIP GUIDELINES - CORE TYPES ONLY:
âš ï¸ CRITICAL: Use ONLY these core relationship types. NO situational descriptors.

FAMILY: parent, child, son, daughter, sibling, brother, sister, spouse, husband, wife
ROMANTIC: lover, partner, boyfriend, girlfriend, of course, lover, partner, boyfriend, girlfriend, ex-lover
SOCIAL: friend, best friend, rival, enemy, acquaintance
PROFESSIONAL: colleague, boss, subordinate, mentor, student, coworker, teammate

âœ… ALLOWED combinations (core types only):
- "Emma is to David: wife, business partner"
- "Marcus is to Elena: brother, protector, friend"
- "Jessica is to Robert: student, friend"
- "Alex is to Morgan: rival, former colleague"

âŒ FORBIDDEN situational/descriptive terms:
- "sexual participant", "dominant", "submissive" (use "lover" or "partner" instead)
- "observer", "witness", "bystander" (not relationships)
- "debt collector", "rescuer", "helper" (actions, not relationships)
- "challenge giver", "organizer" (roles, not relationships)

CRITICAL: Relationships describe permanent social/familial standing ONLY.
Use canonical character names from lorebook. NEVER use aliases in relationship strings.

Rules:
- One entry per distinct person. NEVER combine two different people into one entry.
- If the same person is referred by variants ("John", "John Blackwell", "Scout"), make ONE entry with name = best full name ("John Blackwell") and put other names in aliases.
- Do NOT create names like "Jade/Jesse" or "Sarah and Maya". Instead, create separate entries: [{"name":"Jade"}, {"name":"Jesse"}].
- Only extract clearly named speaking characters.
- Skip generic references ("the waiter", "a woman").
- Use most recent information for conflicts.
- Empty array if no clear characters: {"characters":[]}
- Confidence: 90+ (explicit), 70-89 (clear), 50-69 (mentioned), <50 (vague).

FIELD EXAMPLES:

NAME EXAMPLES:
âœ… "John Blackwood" (not "John Blackwood, John")
âœ… "Maria Santos" (not "Maria/Marie")
âœ… "Alex" (when full name unknown)

ALIAS EXAMPLES:
âœ… ["John", "Scout", "JB"]
âœ… ["Marie", "Maria"]
âœ… ["Mom", "Mother", "Sarah"]

RELATIONSHIP EXAMPLES:
âœ… ["Dora is to John Blackwood: lover, submissive", "Maya is to Sarah Chen: sister, gymnastics partner"]
âŒ ["Lives in penthouse", "Writing novels", "Leading group", "Met at bar"]
âŒ ["Dora, John, lover", "John, Jasmine, friend"] (OLD TRIPLET FORMAT - NEVER USE)
âŒ ["Dora is to John: lover", "Dora is to John Blackwood: submissive"] (split relationships)

We are given several messages. We need to extract character information and return ONLY a JSON object.
 The instructions state:
   - Extract character information from messages
   - Return ONLY a JSON object
   - Use the required format with specific field rules

 Steps:
 1. Identify characters mentioned in the messages: John and Jasmine (as per the current lorebook, and they appear in these messages).
 2. Check for NEW information about these characters. If a character has no new information, do not include them (except John, who must always be included even if minimal).

 Important: The Current Lorebook Entries are provided and we must not repeat unchanged information. Only include if there are updates.

 Analysis of messages for new information:

 John:
   - Always present as "I" or "my", referring to himself.
   - In Message 1, he is speaking and touching Jasmine.
   - Message 3: He pulls Jasmine close and kisses her, and cums inside her.
   - Message 5: He expresses a nonchalant attitude about the possibility of pregnancy, suggesting a child might be a good thing.
   - Message 7: He reassures Jasmine that she is beautiful and strong and that he admires her.

 New information about John?
   - He seems to be the one taking charge in the sexual encounter, being dominant and commanding.
   - He shows care for Jasmine (Messages 5 and 9).
   - His plan includes taking care of her and checking on friends.

 However, note that the current lorebook for John already states:
   - Personality: "Observant helpful concerned dominant commanding possessive"
   - Relationship with Jasmine: multiple entries including "master, recipient"

 The new messages do not seem to change his personality or add significant new traits. They reinforce existing traits.

 Therefore, for John: we are required to include him even with minimal details. But if there is no change, we can just report what we know without change.

 Jasmine:
   - Message 2: She is panicking but gives in to desire and explicitly asks John to cum inside her.
   - Message 4: She expresses shock and then pleasure at the creampie, and worries about pregnancy but also seems fascinated and turned on.
   - Message 6: She shows vulnerability and admits that she liked John's compliments. She also jokes about a potential child.
   - Message 8: She expresses genuine affection for John and wonders about their future relationship. She says she "really likes" him.
   - Message 10: She agrees to the plan to take care of each other and suggests a shower together.

 New information about Jasmine:
   - Her personality during and after the encounter: she becomes vulnerable, honest, and shows affection.
   - Her feelings toward John evolve from lust to something more meaningful.
   - She now identifies with having been "bred" and seems to accept the possibility of pregnancy as part of the experience.

 However, looking at the existing lore for Jasmine:
   - Personality: "Normally confident powerful athlete, now panic-stricken vulnerable embarrassed pliant lustful insatiable wild triumphant grin, currently completely lost in sensation, slutty submissive desperate, vulnerable confused"

 The messages reinforce this and add nuance (like the genuine affection in message 8). But the core personality traits (vulnerable, desperate, etc.) are already present.

 Important: The instruction says only include if NEW information appears.

# Character Extraction

I analyzed the conversation to extract information about each character mentioned in the messages. After careful review, I found that only one character had new information revealed during this interaction.

## Dora
Dora is described as having a "leaner athletic figure" with olive skin and freckles. She has C-cup breasts that are still swollen with lactation. During this conversation, she shows a personality shift from defiant to vulnerable and needy. The messages reveal her as bi-curious with a Latina ethnicity, serving as a team member and track captain. Her relationships include being a teammate to Jasmine, a roommate/lover/nurse to Rosa, and a teammate to Jade. She is also described as having a 90% confidence level based on her explicit participation and reactions.

The extraction captures only the new information about Dora since John is the user character and would always be included, while the other characters (Jasmine, Jade, Rosa) did not have significant changes in their attributes or relationships during this interaction.</think>```json
